531
00:49:27,170 --> 00:49:41,055
[SPEAKER_00]: Francis, did you get the answer to your question about what you wanted from the commission for, I guess, for a swag for our materials?

532
00:49:41,235 --> 00:49:42,255
[SPEAKER_12]: No, I didn't.

533
00:49:42,275 --> 00:49:46,557
[SPEAKER_12]: I was simply also just asking if that's okay with you.

534
00:49:46,577 --> 00:49:51,218
[SPEAKER_12]: Okay.

535
00:49:51,418 --> 00:49:52,179
[SPEAKER_00]: It's okay with me.

536
00:49:52,259 --> 00:49:55,540
[SPEAKER_00]: Do you want us to take a vote?

537
00:49:57,668 --> 00:50:05,292
[SPEAKER_12]: Not necessarily a vote, but it would be nice to get some ideas from people for because this is this is just really about the commission.

538
00:50:05,332 --> 00:50:07,793
[SPEAKER_12]: And this is just a short term temporary fix.

539
00:50:07,853 --> 00:50:11,775
[SPEAKER_12]: And I don't want to you know, I don't want to over order, you know.

540
00:50:11,895 --> 00:50:17,538
[SPEAKER_12]: So what would you be interested in in, you know, short term swag for right now?

541
00:50:18,699 --> 00:50:20,660
[SPEAKER_12]: For this, you know, for this event?

542
00:50:21,282 --> 00:50:28,684
[SPEAKER_12]: and to know that that swag would really just be the city seal with the words commission on persons with disabilities.

543
00:50:30,184 --> 00:50:31,144
[SPEAKER_11]: That's fine with me.

544
00:50:33,525 --> 00:50:38,005
[SPEAKER_11]: So Francis, are you asking for suggestions on what you should get?

545
00:50:39,906 --> 00:50:41,766
[SPEAKER_12]: Suggestions would be welcome as well.

546
00:50:41,946 --> 00:50:46,687
[SPEAKER_12]: It shouldn't be, it shouldn't be the city liaison's decision, right?

547
00:50:46,767 --> 00:50:50,248
[SPEAKER_12]: So I'm giving you ideas and I'm waiting for feedback.

548
00:50:50,922 --> 00:50:51,542
[SPEAKER_11]: Oh, okay then.

549
00:50:52,043 --> 00:50:58,527
[SPEAKER_11]: So, okay, if I throw out something, I would say something that is useful, right?

550
00:50:59,088 --> 00:51:06,092
[SPEAKER_11]: And maybe a towel with the little pin in it, the circle in it, because you can always use a towel.

551
00:51:06,493 --> 00:51:07,894
[SPEAKER_11]: You know, those little hand towels?

552
00:51:08,834 --> 00:51:14,438
[SPEAKER_11]: And with our name on it, the seal, and contact information, a website or something.

553
00:51:15,661 --> 00:51:17,642
[SPEAKER_12]: So this is short term, right?

554
00:51:18,123 --> 00:51:21,665
[SPEAKER_12]: So I think this is not the one that has your real logo yet.

555
00:51:22,145 --> 00:51:23,606
[SPEAKER_12]: So, you know, more ideas.

556
00:51:23,626 --> 00:51:24,387
[SPEAKER_12]: Do you want magnets?

557
00:51:24,407 --> 00:51:25,168
[SPEAKER_12]: Do you want pens?

558
00:51:25,208 --> 00:51:25,808
[SPEAKER_12]: Do you want water?

559
00:51:26,008 --> 00:51:29,190
[SPEAKER_12]: You know, because I have to now go on and find some items.

560
00:51:29,250 --> 00:51:33,053
[SPEAKER_12]: So that's, yeah.

561
00:51:33,073 --> 00:51:43,240
[SPEAKER_06]: I think a pen and a little pad of paper would be nice so that people can write down

562
00:51:43,812 --> 00:51:50,779
[SPEAKER_06]: any information that they get during the resource fair.

563
00:51:54,122 --> 00:52:07,094
[SPEAKER_01]: On the paper, I don't know if this makes, I was actually thinking, Gabby, when you mentioned the Perkins School for the Blind, I know on their business cards, it's in Braille.

564
00:52:08,529 --> 00:52:22,518
[SPEAKER_01]: And I was thinking it might be cool if we had some sort of contact, something like that contact, since we're the commission for disability, you know, persons with disabilities, if there was something that we had in Braille or something tactile like that.

565
00:52:22,538 --> 00:52:26,721
[SPEAKER_01]: I mean, I don't, I don't think like a pen and a pad of paper, I think that would be a little ironic.

566
00:52:27,701 --> 00:52:37,788
[SPEAKER_01]: Um, although maybe I'm speaking out of place, but I, you know, if there's like a contact card, um, that would also have Braille on it, that could be kind of cool.

567
00:52:41,774 --> 00:52:45,475
[SPEAKER_08]: Yeah, I have the capability to do that at work.

568
00:52:46,375 --> 00:52:51,376
[SPEAKER_08]: Um, I don't know what day I will be back during the week.

569
00:52:51,476 --> 00:52:52,456
[SPEAKER_08]: I can look at my schedule.

570
00:52:53,076 --> 00:52:57,597
[SPEAKER_08]: Um, if not also the national Braille press in Boston, uh, takes customized orders.

571
00:52:57,997 --> 00:53:00,078
[SPEAKER_08]: Um, and they're usually pretty quick with the turnaround.

572
00:53:00,798 --> 00:53:02,198
[SPEAKER_08]: Um, so I can definitely look into that.

573
00:53:03,979 --> 00:53:04,859
[SPEAKER_11]: That sounds cool.

574
00:53:04,879 --> 00:53:08,800
[SPEAKER_11]: I mean, because that just really makes it so inclusive.

575
00:53:09,200 --> 00:53:09,520
[SPEAKER_11]: People will,

576
00:53:11,119 --> 00:53:18,064
[SPEAKER_11]: it will open up another world to individuals, you know, having something and knowing what it actually says and feeling it.

577
00:53:18,564 --> 00:53:19,104
[SPEAKER_11]: That's cool.

578
00:53:23,387 --> 00:53:26,329
[SPEAKER_02]: Any other thoughts for Frances on SWAG?

579
00:53:38,997 --> 00:53:40,218
[SPEAKER_02]: Frances, is that enough to work with?

580
00:53:42,601 --> 00:53:43,041
[SPEAKER_02]: I do.

581
00:53:43,061 --> 00:53:44,382
[SPEAKER_02]: All right.

582
00:53:46,522 --> 00:53:49,703
[SPEAKER_00]: I see flyer on the list, too.

583
00:53:49,723 --> 00:53:52,004
[SPEAKER_00]: Do we do we need someone to design the flyer?

584
00:53:52,024 --> 00:53:54,685
[SPEAKER_02]: Well.

585
00:53:57,146 --> 00:53:57,446
[SPEAKER_02]: Hmm.

586
00:54:00,807 --> 00:54:09,850
[SPEAKER_12]: If no, I can have the consign design the flyer so that we can get it out as soon as possible, it will just be just a very basic flyer.

587
00:54:10,412 --> 00:54:23,637
[SPEAKER_12]: But I can have them something that we can use for social media and for the calendar.

588
00:54:23,677 --> 00:54:27,678
[SPEAKER_00]: Do we know how we're going to publicize this?

589
00:54:27,758 --> 00:54:31,620
[SPEAKER_00]: I don't know if we need to brainstorm some ideas of where to post it.

590
00:54:36,234 --> 00:54:43,718
[SPEAKER_12]: The city would obviously do it on the social media, the calendar, our own individualized contact list.

591
00:54:43,758 --> 00:54:50,882
[SPEAKER_12]: But I think that as commissioners, if you have outlets and networks, it should be shared that way as well.

592
00:54:50,902 --> 00:54:54,504
[SPEAKER_11]: Excuse the question.

593
00:54:54,584 --> 00:54:56,325
[SPEAKER_11]: Will you all be printing up flyers?

594
00:54:57,719 --> 00:55:07,668
[SPEAKER_12]: Or is this all we typically just do online, we do very few, very few runs of hard copies, unless they're going to like a specific place.

595
00:55:14,874 --> 00:55:18,257
[SPEAKER_00]: All right, so that I like that idea, for instance, when when it's done.

596
00:55:19,137 --> 00:55:21,619
[SPEAKER_00]: If you need feedback on it, I'm happy to provide feedback.

597
00:55:22,340 --> 00:55:24,382
[SPEAKER_00]: But then we can send it to all the commissioners and we can

598
00:55:25,563 --> 00:55:29,385
[SPEAKER_00]: post it in the social media spots that we visit.

599
00:55:30,405 --> 00:55:36,648
[SPEAKER_10]: So I feel like when the mayor calls with the announcements, she does it about every two weeks.

600
00:55:37,348 --> 00:55:38,229
[SPEAKER_10]: I get a phone call.

601
00:55:39,669 --> 00:55:43,951
[SPEAKER_10]: Definitely would be great to have that included in the phone call on April.

602
00:55:44,251 --> 00:55:44,752
[SPEAKER_10]: I'm sorry.

603
00:55:46,752 --> 00:55:50,414
[SPEAKER_12]: That's all part of the outreach.

604
00:55:51,795 --> 00:55:53,876
[SPEAKER_12]: The road calls, the video.

605
00:55:56,430 --> 00:56:02,172
[SPEAKER_12]: I think it's the videos are now done weekly so that will all be included, or be mentioned.

606
00:56:02,692 --> 00:56:08,554
[SPEAKER_12]: If you look I believe it's already on the city calendar, even though we don't have a fly.

607
00:56:10,054 --> 00:56:12,855
[SPEAKER_02]: That's all part of the communications package.

608
00:56:16,976 --> 00:56:17,817
[SPEAKER_02]: Awesome, Marcia.

609
00:56:19,997 --> 00:56:29,083
[SPEAKER_13]: I was wondering if there might be a small amount of money to advertise in things like a pack where you have to pay to get prominent announcements.

610
00:56:30,344 --> 00:56:35,247
[SPEAKER_13]: You can get one for nothing, but it doesn't show up in any other pocket.

611
00:56:35,387 --> 00:56:37,228
[SPEAKER_13]: It's inexpensive, like $25.

612
00:56:37,929 --> 00:56:41,311
[SPEAKER_02]: It's not huge, or it used to be not huge.

613
00:56:46,234 --> 00:56:47,975
[SPEAKER_02]: Francis, do you have a budget for advertising?

614
00:56:51,987 --> 00:56:54,288
[SPEAKER_02]: We don't really have a budget for advertising.

615
00:56:55,968 --> 00:56:59,329
[SPEAKER_12]: Where would you be suggesting that we advertise?

616
00:56:59,629 --> 00:57:01,790
[SPEAKER_13]: Well, that's one place that comes to mind.

617
00:57:03,550 --> 00:57:11,812
[SPEAKER_13]: I would have to think about that some more.

618
00:57:12,132 --> 00:57:18,194
[SPEAKER_13]: I'm not sure there are many other places where you pay, except that would be really big.

619
00:57:19,494 --> 00:57:21,495
[SPEAKER_13]: And I don't think they could discover that.

620
00:57:22,487 --> 00:57:26,050
[SPEAKER_12]: I'm sorry, Marsha, I'm having difficulty hearing you.

621
00:57:26,090 --> 00:57:28,051
[SPEAKER_12]: You're not coming through clearly.

622
00:57:28,071 --> 00:57:31,213
[SPEAKER_12]: Is everybody able to hear Marsha clearly?

623
00:57:31,233 --> 00:57:31,273
[SPEAKER_12]: No.

624
00:57:34,415 --> 00:57:35,937
[SPEAKER_12]: I can't do anything else.

625
00:57:36,277 --> 00:57:38,578
[SPEAKER_13]: OK, now I can hear you a little bit better.

626
00:57:38,598 --> 00:57:40,640
[SPEAKER_13]: I moved it toward me.

627
00:57:41,661 --> 00:57:43,001
[SPEAKER_13]: I won't think.

628
00:57:43,702 --> 00:57:44,422
[SPEAKER_13]: Oh, OK.

629
00:57:44,763 --> 00:57:46,224
[SPEAKER_13]: Now you're clearer.

630
00:57:47,305 --> 00:57:50,787
[SPEAKER_13]: I was suggesting the patch, which you can advertise in.

631
00:57:52,672 --> 00:57:53,673
[SPEAKER_13]: more prominently.

632
00:57:53,693 --> 00:57:59,678
[SPEAKER_13]: You used to be able to get a free ad, but it's amongst many other events.

633
00:57:59,998 --> 00:58:00,919
[SPEAKER_13]: It's an event source.

634
00:58:03,661 --> 00:58:09,806
[SPEAKER_12]: I don't know about advertising in the patch, but why don't I talk to comms and see, because I know comms usually works with the patch.

635
00:58:10,927 --> 00:58:18,573
[SPEAKER_12]: So if they can, you know, if it's not something that, you know, where we can put a fly, but how about something along the lines of a press release,

636
00:58:21,158 --> 00:58:24,679
[SPEAKER_12]: does make spaces such as the Patch.

637
00:58:26,140 --> 00:58:32,082
[SPEAKER_13]: I don't think the Patch is doing so many things like that anymore, specifically in Medford.

638
00:58:33,242 --> 00:58:35,003
[SPEAKER_13]: I'm sorry, I'm not hearing again.

639
00:58:35,023 --> 00:58:45,386
[SPEAKER_13]: I think the Patch has moved away from only having Medford news and having more regional news, just so you know.

640
00:58:47,367 --> 00:58:49,988
[SPEAKER_07]: Frances, is there a budget for the Disability Commission at all?

641
00:58:50,901 --> 00:58:53,984
[SPEAKER_12]: No, there isn't a budget for the Disability Commission.

642
00:58:54,044 --> 00:58:56,586
[SPEAKER_12]: There hasn't been one for the Disability Commission.

643
00:58:56,606 --> 00:58:58,969
[SPEAKER_09]: Do any of the other commissions have a budget?

644
00:58:59,209 --> 00:58:59,469
[SPEAKER_12]: Sorry.

645
00:58:59,609 --> 00:59:03,333
[SPEAKER_12]: I acquired the two commissions that I have do not have a budget.

646
00:59:04,394 --> 00:59:06,495
[SPEAKER_09]: Do you know if any of the other commissions have a budget?

647
00:59:06,996 --> 00:59:09,018
[SPEAKER_12]: Some commissions have budgets, some don't.

648
00:59:09,338 --> 00:59:11,020
[SPEAKER_12]: The ones that I have don't have budgets.

649
00:59:12,821 --> 00:59:16,565
[SPEAKER_09]: And if we wanted to find out which commissions had budgets, how would we do that?

650
00:59:17,198 --> 00:59:21,861
[SPEAKER_12]: I think that you can see it online, you can see where the stipends are assigned to people.

651
00:59:22,481 --> 00:59:24,582
[SPEAKER_13]: Okay.

652
00:59:24,602 --> 00:59:28,164
[SPEAKER_12]: So I just, I just want to be clear and I just want to remind everyone.

653
00:59:28,364 --> 00:59:43,272
[SPEAKER_12]: So when ARPA was issued, I requested some funds from ARPA funding for the committee, but for specific things.

654
00:59:45,111 --> 00:59:47,411
[SPEAKER_12]: So that's the money that we have.

655
00:59:47,491 --> 00:59:55,933
[SPEAKER_12]: If you remember, I had expressed that I was going to request this because we felt like we were going to do a logo, we were going to have some identity.

656
00:59:56,393 --> 00:59:58,274
[SPEAKER_12]: So that's what we have, Melanie.

657
00:59:58,314 --> 01:00:01,994
[SPEAKER_12]: But you know that once that's done, that's not replaceable.

658
01:00:02,054 --> 01:00:08,576
[SPEAKER_12]: When ARPA ends on the 31st of December next year, it's gone.

659
01:00:08,836 --> 01:00:13,717
[SPEAKER_12]: And when the funds that were requested are expended,

660
01:00:14,578 --> 01:00:14,998
[SPEAKER_12]: That's it.

661
01:00:16,479 --> 01:00:23,123
[SPEAKER_09]: Well, or the commission can make a vote and someone can make a motion to request more funds and people could vote on whether they want to do that.

662
01:00:23,263 --> 01:00:24,624
[SPEAKER_09]: So there's always that option.

663
01:00:24,664 --> 01:00:35,331
[SPEAKER_09]: But again, I think it's getting ahead of, you know, the cart getting ahead of the horse, if you will, in terms of, you know, the event for the, um, this particular fair, but I think it begs the question.

664
01:00:35,411 --> 01:00:41,495
[SPEAKER_09]: I think, you know, the commission might want to think about whether you, whether the budget is needed and for what, and,

665
01:00:42,360 --> 01:00:45,142
[SPEAKER_09]: how to go about getting one if you want one.

666
01:00:45,282 --> 01:00:47,923
[SPEAKER_09]: I think that's important for you all to consider.

667
01:00:47,943 --> 01:00:54,587
[SPEAKER_00]: I know we only have about 20 minutes left and we have a couple other agenda items.

668
01:00:55,108 --> 01:00:58,069
[SPEAKER_00]: I think that is important to have a budget.

669
01:00:58,109 --> 01:01:00,711
[SPEAKER_00]: I'm glad we have some funds for April 29th.

670
01:01:02,051 --> 01:01:09,656
[SPEAKER_00]: I know that our next meeting is not till, I think three days before the event.

671
01:01:09,696 --> 01:01:10,676
[SPEAKER_00]: So we have our,

672
01:01:11,868 --> 01:01:14,149
[SPEAKER_00]: you know, a number of things planned between now and then.

673
01:01:14,169 --> 01:01:24,696
[SPEAKER_00]: Is there anything else that is on someone's mind about the resource pride day that we need to discuss before we move on?

674
01:01:24,716 --> 01:01:29,098
[SPEAKER_11]: I do have a quick question.

675
01:01:29,118 --> 01:01:34,822
[SPEAKER_11]: I know that now I'm hearing this bit about the budgets and being mindful of the finances.

676
01:01:34,842 --> 01:01:40,085
[SPEAKER_11]: Is something as, you know, for when we talk about SWAG, Francis,

677
01:01:40,508 --> 01:01:45,793
[SPEAKER_11]: maybe something with just a QR code leading everybody back to, you know, our website.

678
01:01:46,113 --> 01:01:48,655
[SPEAKER_11]: And then that could be something that's very simple.

679
01:01:48,996 --> 01:01:51,838
[SPEAKER_11]: We're not spending a lot of money and maybe it's done.

680
01:01:52,298 --> 01:01:58,244
[SPEAKER_11]: You know, I don't know if it can be done in braille and just a QR code and a piece of paper in a sense.

681
01:01:58,624 --> 01:02:01,847
[SPEAKER_11]: And it's very simple, but that's all I wanted to say about that.

682
01:02:01,987 --> 01:02:02,387
[SPEAKER_11]: Thank you.

683
01:02:03,328 --> 01:02:04,930
[SPEAKER_10]: I love that QR code.

684
01:02:05,750 --> 01:02:07,592
[SPEAKER_10]: And then it'll access a lot of people.

685
01:02:09,642 --> 01:02:10,923
[SPEAKER_11]: go directly to our site.

686
01:02:11,143 --> 01:02:19,189
[SPEAKER_11]: And then, you know, it's not you don't have to worry about what you should buy Francis, you know, a pen, you know, the towel or whatever.

687
01:02:19,209 --> 01:02:21,751
[SPEAKER_11]: And they could be still used.

688
01:02:24,573 --> 01:02:32,759
[SPEAKER_00]: All right, so we should move on to the next agenda item unless you're up.

689
01:02:34,670 --> 01:02:35,631
[SPEAKER_00]: We just lost Francis.

690
01:02:37,332 --> 01:02:41,874
[SPEAKER_00]: I was going to ask if Francis had something else, but we'll move on to the next agenda item.

691
01:02:44,136 --> 01:02:51,520
[SPEAKER_00]: Susie, do you want to give a short summary of your meeting with Sam at the library?

692
01:02:51,980 --> 01:02:52,220
[SPEAKER_00]: Yes.

693
01:02:52,620 --> 01:02:54,522
[SPEAKER_10]: I just have to shift and get my notes.

694
01:02:56,583 --> 01:03:02,286
[SPEAKER_00]: I'll just quickly let you guys know that Susie and I went and met with Sam.

695
01:03:04,595 --> 01:03:11,260
[SPEAKER_00]: who you may know, Sam, the librarian at, I'm not sure what Sam's role is there.

696
01:03:11,980 --> 01:03:16,323
[SPEAKER_00]: But I was there for like three minutes, and then Susie ended up meeting with Sam.

697
01:03:17,824 --> 01:03:22,688
[SPEAKER_00]: And we've learned about a number of resources that the library has available.

698
01:03:22,708 --> 01:03:24,849
[SPEAKER_00]: So yeah, I don't know if you can.

699
01:03:25,249 --> 01:03:27,031
[SPEAKER_10]: I was absolutely bowled over.

700
01:03:27,051 --> 01:03:30,233
[SPEAKER_10]: So they have homebound delivery.

701
01:03:32,043 --> 01:03:35,305
[SPEAKER_10]: and they have technology support.

702
01:03:36,446 --> 01:03:41,490
[SPEAKER_10]: They have students coming in from Tufts to do technology support.

703
01:03:42,410 --> 01:03:49,115
[SPEAKER_10]: They have youth services where they have quiet spaces for kids who have sensory issues.

704
01:03:50,135 --> 01:03:52,157
[SPEAKER_10]: They have a sensory story hour.

705
01:03:52,957 --> 01:03:57,240
[SPEAKER_10]: They have teaching computer lab for all ages.

706
01:03:58,201 --> 01:03:58,981
[SPEAKER_10]: They have

707
01:04:01,400 --> 01:04:08,184
[SPEAKER_10]: Oh my goodness, they have, Homebound, they have, they want volunteers.

708
01:04:09,405 --> 01:04:11,206
[SPEAKER_10]: I didn't have any idea about this.

709
01:04:11,867 --> 01:04:30,819
[SPEAKER_10]: Chapters Coffee Cart, which is upstairs on the second floor, where they do a lot of the technology and story hours and maybe the art spaces, that is personed by people with disabilities.

710
01:04:32,137 --> 01:04:44,402
[SPEAKER_10]: And not only do they employ disabled, they also, that money also supports the endeavors of people with disabilities.

711
01:04:45,562 --> 01:04:56,206
[SPEAKER_10]: And they have things where they have books and games and audios and movies.

712
01:04:56,995 --> 01:04:59,717
[SPEAKER_10]: that they circulate for people.

713
01:05:00,458 --> 01:05:07,964
[SPEAKER_10]: I was astounded and they keep like very current.

714
01:05:08,084 --> 01:05:12,767
[SPEAKER_10]: I stopped teaching officially special education about four and a half years ago.

715
01:05:13,568 --> 01:05:23,336
[SPEAKER_10]: And I kept, I was trying to listen to Sam, Tom, but I kept looking at all the games, hands-on family game boxes they had.

716
01:05:25,073 --> 01:05:31,018
[SPEAKER_10]: of things that would teach kids cooperative play, sensory stuff, and so on.

717
01:05:32,039 --> 01:05:42,208
[SPEAKER_10]: And I don't know about the whole library, but Sam is definitely embracing the whole disability community.

718
01:05:42,849 --> 01:05:51,837
[SPEAKER_10]: And I said, well, what we're trying to do, and I know Yvette and I talked about this a lot, is we have all these fractures in Medford.

719
01:05:52,243 --> 01:06:02,690
[SPEAKER_10]: You have the senior center, you have the library, you have the med, uh, med rec, you have all these different places are doing triangle that are doing things.

720
01:06:03,230 --> 01:06:15,159
[SPEAKER_10]: Oh, here's Yvette was the, um, West Medford, uh, senior center doing different things for seniors and for, uh, disabled, but we've got to get it all together.

721
01:06:16,099 --> 01:06:20,062
[SPEAKER_10]: And I think Yvette and I really talked about that and Sam at the library,

722
01:06:21,086 --> 01:06:24,987
[SPEAKER_10]: totally agreed with me that we've got to pull it all together.

723
01:06:25,567 --> 01:06:33,270
[SPEAKER_10]: And I'm hoping in this next year between our board and between different things that will happen.

724
01:06:33,790 --> 01:06:35,491
[SPEAKER_10]: That's my vision of it all.

725
01:06:36,711 --> 01:06:37,691
[SPEAKER_10]: I think it's Yvette's.

726
01:06:38,051 --> 01:06:39,712
[SPEAKER_10]: Yes, Yvette?

727
01:06:40,432 --> 01:06:41,092
[SPEAKER_10]: It's ours.

728
01:06:41,112 --> 01:06:42,373
[SPEAKER_10]: It's a team.

729
01:06:42,833 --> 01:06:43,093
[SPEAKER_10]: Yes.

730
01:06:45,013 --> 01:06:49,695
[SPEAKER_10]: Anyway, the library made me really feel excited by it.

731
01:06:50,448 --> 01:06:53,829
[SPEAKER_00]: And I'll just thank you for that summary.

732
01:06:53,990 --> 01:06:56,491
[SPEAKER_00]: I'll just add there are some specific dates.

733
01:06:56,871 --> 01:07:09,356
[SPEAKER_00]: On April 8th, from 9 to 12 at the library, they have a high school student who will be there answering questions in their tech lab.

734
01:07:09,956 --> 01:07:13,418
[SPEAKER_00]: And then on the same day,

735
01:07:14,471 --> 01:07:18,615
[SPEAKER_00]: I think they have 68 tough students who are going to- I had that written down.

736
01:07:18,675 --> 01:07:19,095
[SPEAKER_00]: You got it.

737
01:07:19,435 --> 01:07:19,675
[SPEAKER_00]: Great.

738
01:07:19,695 --> 01:07:19,956
[SPEAKER_00]: All right.

739
01:07:19,976 --> 01:07:23,459
[SPEAKER_00]: That's till two o'clock to also field tech questions.

740
01:07:23,539 --> 01:07:26,621
[SPEAKER_00]: So it would probably be good to add to that.

741
01:07:26,681 --> 01:07:37,470
[SPEAKER_00]: It's before our pair, but my impression was from Sam that this may be a recurring thing that's happening there.

742
01:07:38,631 --> 01:07:39,592
[SPEAKER_00]: Melody- It's wonderful.

743
01:07:40,052 --> 01:07:40,333
[SPEAKER_00]: Yeah.

744
01:07:40,693 --> 01:07:41,774
[SPEAKER_00]: Melody, did you want to add something?

745
01:07:45,697 --> 01:07:52,458
[SPEAKER_09]: Yeah, I want to add, I think that that is a fantastic idea and something that I've been dreaming about for Medford for a long time.

746
01:07:52,498 --> 01:07:57,559
[SPEAKER_09]: So I love hearing you say this, Suzanne, and I love hearing that, you know, on board as well.

747
01:07:57,599 --> 01:08:01,280
[SPEAKER_09]: I think it's super important to grab, to get these disparate groups together.

748
01:08:01,380 --> 01:08:14,683
[SPEAKER_09]: And I think one of the themes of the disability pride, you know, could and maybe should be one of the logos or something, slogans could be that, you know, as we hear, as Judy has said, Judy Heumann, as others, you know, say all the time,

749
01:08:15,235 --> 01:08:16,857
[SPEAKER_09]: is that disability is natural.

750
01:08:16,937 --> 01:08:28,811
[SPEAKER_09]: We are ultimately all disabled at some point, whether it's by old age, whether it is by pregnancy, accident, birth, you know, any number of things, we all experience disability at some point.

751
01:08:28,851 --> 01:08:36,260
[SPEAKER_09]: And so I think, you know, helping people understand that we're a community and that we're an inclusive community and that ultimately

752
01:08:36,888 --> 01:08:40,310
[SPEAKER_09]: everyone will be part of our community, whether they realize it or not.

753
01:08:41,071 --> 01:08:50,076
[SPEAKER_09]: And so I think that's really great to really create all these groups coming together and helping them understand that we're all part of it together.

754
01:08:51,717 --> 01:08:54,539
[SPEAKER_10]: Marsha, I see you shaking your head and I'd love to see it.

755
01:08:55,179 --> 01:08:56,520
[SPEAKER_10]: This feels good to you, Marsha?

756
01:08:57,000 --> 01:08:57,521
[SPEAKER_10]: Wonderful.

757
01:08:57,901 --> 01:08:58,181
[SPEAKER_10]: Good.

758
01:08:58,741 --> 01:09:00,082
[SPEAKER_13]: I really love that idea.

759
01:09:00,402 --> 01:09:00,603
[SPEAKER_13]: Good.

760
01:09:02,625 --> 01:09:09,869
[SPEAKER_13]: I wanted to add one more thought that I loved in our last brochure, which if it's still proof answers, I'm not sure.

761
01:09:11,190 --> 01:09:19,555
[SPEAKER_13]: But it was a statement that came out saying Medford supports individuals of all ability.

762
01:09:21,737 --> 01:09:25,719
[SPEAKER_13]: And that was right under whatever design thing we had.

763
01:09:27,739 --> 01:09:31,261
[SPEAKER_13]: It was prominent in the flyer that we made.

764
01:09:31,821 --> 01:09:32,682
[SPEAKER_13]: And I still like it.

765
01:09:32,702 --> 01:09:34,623
[SPEAKER_13]: So I don't know.

766
01:09:37,164 --> 01:09:43,387
[SPEAKER_13]: That's something that other people like and want to keep.

767
01:09:43,608 --> 01:09:44,808
[SPEAKER_13]: But I do.

768
01:09:46,009 --> 01:09:46,409
[SPEAKER_13]: That's it.

769
01:09:48,030 --> 01:09:48,450
[SPEAKER_00]: Thank you.

770
01:09:51,072 --> 01:09:52,993
[SPEAKER_00]: I think that summarizes it well.

771
01:09:53,033 --> 01:09:56,855
[SPEAKER_00]: I think the key is getting this information out to people.

772
01:09:57,972 --> 01:10:05,555
[SPEAKER_00]: Um, uh, Gabby, I don't know if you're able to, to talk, but I know that, um, when it makes you Linda, you might be aware, right?

773
01:10:05,575 --> 01:10:11,417
[SPEAKER_00]: We put together this database of emails, um, that we've collected over the past year or so.

774
01:10:12,238 --> 01:10:17,900
[SPEAKER_00]: Um, is there a way that we can send out this information to the folks on that, on that list?

775
01:10:19,861 --> 01:10:20,161
[SPEAKER_01]: Yes.

776
01:10:20,301 --> 01:10:21,702
[SPEAKER_01]: Can you hear me?

777
01:10:22,242 --> 01:10:23,082
[SPEAKER_01]: Yeah, we can hear you, Gabby.

778
01:10:23,102 --> 01:10:23,362
[SPEAKER_01]: Go ahead.

779
01:10:24,143 --> 01:10:24,423
[SPEAKER_07]: Sorry.

780
01:10:24,463 --> 01:10:25,083
[SPEAKER_01]: No, go ahead.

781
01:10:27,125 --> 01:10:30,026
[SPEAKER_01]: Oh, I think you're talking about the MailChimp account.

782
01:10:30,446 --> 01:10:32,547
[SPEAKER_01]: And I think that's still active.

783
01:10:33,428 --> 01:10:35,708
[SPEAKER_01]: So I'd have to just double check.

784
01:10:35,749 --> 01:10:37,349
[SPEAKER_01]: I don't see why it wouldn't be active.

785
01:10:37,809 --> 01:10:47,733
[SPEAKER_01]: So we could send an email out to that effect if someone wants to write up what we want or just compile information.

786
01:10:47,933 --> 01:10:52,955
[SPEAKER_01]: I'm happy to start a Google Doc if people want to throw ideas in there or if someone already has an idea.

787
01:10:55,406 --> 01:11:07,870
[SPEAKER_01]: then what we want to say, then, you know, feel free to go nuts and create a Google Doc, and then I can put it into the MailChimp and send it out.

788
01:11:08,670 --> 01:11:21,374
[SPEAKER_00]: Yeah, I've just been thinking with the, obviously we want to get the information out about the resource fair to that list, but also these other events that are going, other events at the library that are going on, it'd probably be good to write them all up.

789
01:11:23,142 --> 01:11:32,284
[SPEAKER_00]: I can, Sam summarized the meeting with Susie in an email, so we can easily, you know, kind of copy and paste that information.

790
01:11:32,304 --> 01:11:36,085
[SPEAKER_00]: So I don't know, Linda, you said you're up for starting the Google Doc?

791
01:11:36,145 --> 01:11:39,326
[SPEAKER_00]: If you could do that, I can just paste the stuff on there.

792
01:11:42,146 --> 01:11:42,966
[SPEAKER_10]: Tom, go for it.

793
01:11:43,386 --> 01:11:46,967
[SPEAKER_10]: I'm away right now, so go for it.

794
01:11:47,327 --> 01:11:47,807
[SPEAKER_00]: That'd be great.

795
01:11:50,168 --> 01:11:51,248
[SPEAKER_00]: Did somebody raise their hand?

796
01:11:52,463 --> 01:11:52,683
[SPEAKER_00]: No?

797
01:11:52,943 --> 01:11:53,204
[SPEAKER_00]: All right.

798
01:11:54,284 --> 01:11:59,008
[SPEAKER_00]: All right, so we should move on to the next item.

799
01:11:59,028 --> 01:12:00,309
[SPEAKER_00]: We have about 10 minutes left.

800
01:12:01,690 --> 01:12:08,275
[SPEAKER_00]: Marcia, did you want to share what your piece about Judy?

801
01:12:09,575 --> 01:12:13,638
[SPEAKER_13]: Well, it's actually not quite about Judy.

802
01:12:13,799 --> 01:12:19,062
[SPEAKER_13]: I was thought, since I think I'm the only person who lived through the 60s in this.

803
01:12:19,363 --> 01:12:19,703
[SPEAKER_06]: It was?

804
01:12:20,530 --> 01:12:29,855
[SPEAKER_13]: I'm the only person who was in college starting in 1959, when the Civil Rights Movement was very active.

805
01:12:31,196 --> 01:12:47,446
[SPEAKER_13]: And I thought maybe just sharing a little bit of some of the strategies that were used then might, and I'm sure that Judy must have adapted, might pertain to some of the things we might need today.

806
01:12:50,801 --> 01:13:08,315
[SPEAKER_13]: And I'm sure you all know that Martin Luther King was the leader of the Civil Rights Movement, and he was a very vocally adept and kind of uniting force.

807
01:13:09,375 --> 01:13:12,578
[SPEAKER_13]: And I thought that was one instrumental thing.

808
01:13:13,679 --> 01:13:19,203
[SPEAKER_13]: And of course, there were a lot of marches, many marches, a lot of the time.

809
01:13:19,971 --> 01:13:30,254
[SPEAKER_13]: But as I've been thinking about it, and I'm sure that Judy did so much more than that, there is much more required to accomplish a goal like that.

810
01:13:31,374 --> 01:13:38,576
[SPEAKER_13]: And one of the things that happened, first of all, was this was all, or the main part of it was peaceful.

811
01:13:38,676 --> 01:13:47,558
[SPEAKER_13]: There were fringe groups that were not peaceful, but mostly it was, and there were,

812
01:13:48,947 --> 01:13:53,931
[SPEAKER_13]: There was a lot of information put out, like our fair.

813
01:13:54,491 --> 01:13:59,855
[SPEAKER_13]: There was a lot of politics being played at that time.

814
01:14:01,055 --> 01:14:11,863
[SPEAKER_13]: So the people, leaders of the movement, met with people high up in our federal government.

815
01:14:12,690 --> 01:14:24,254
[SPEAKER_13]: And I believe that a lot of participants went to Washington to meet with their representatives and senators.

816
01:14:24,774 --> 01:14:30,115
[SPEAKER_13]: So there was also a lot of political pressure.

817
01:14:31,156 --> 01:14:33,837
[SPEAKER_13]: So all these things were happening at the same time.

818
01:14:39,643 --> 01:14:45,147
[SPEAKER_13]: I am sure that Judy knew some of these strategies because she was a child of the time.

819
01:14:45,848 --> 01:14:48,730
[SPEAKER_13]: And that's really what I wanted to say.

820
01:14:49,250 --> 01:14:58,177
[SPEAKER_13]: I think it's a lesson for us, her life and some of the civil rights issues that persisted.

821
01:15:03,921 --> 01:15:05,863
[SPEAKER_02]: And I think that's exactly what you see in Crip Camp.

822
01:15:07,006 --> 01:15:08,587
[SPEAKER_09]: You know, that's exactly what you see in Crip Camp.

823
01:15:08,607 --> 01:15:11,429
[SPEAKER_09]: Thank you for sharing that, Marsha, because it's so true and it's so motivating.

824
01:15:11,489 --> 01:15:18,554
[SPEAKER_09]: And when you really see the, you know, disability rights and civil rights, I think it puts everything in a whole different perspective.

825
01:15:18,654 --> 01:15:20,216
[SPEAKER_09]: So thank you so much for sharing that.

826
01:15:20,236 --> 01:15:22,177
[SPEAKER_13]: You're welcome.

827
01:15:22,737 --> 01:15:24,218
[SPEAKER_13]: I like the time.

828
01:15:26,260 --> 01:15:28,922
[SPEAKER_13]: And I wish I had it in me to be in a march.

829
01:15:29,522 --> 01:15:33,825
[SPEAKER_13]: I keep thinking of marching in a wheelchair, but then I need someone to push me.

830
01:15:34,346 --> 01:15:35,907
[SPEAKER_13]: So it goes on and on.

831
01:15:37,307 --> 01:15:39,068
[SPEAKER_09]: I'll push you any day, Marsha.

832
01:15:39,728 --> 01:15:40,969
[SPEAKER_09]: Which March do you prefer?

833
01:15:43,349 --> 01:15:45,890
[SPEAKER_02]: We have to figure that one out.

834
01:15:47,871 --> 01:15:49,452
[SPEAKER_00]: Thank you, Marsha.

835
01:15:50,592 --> 01:15:56,414
[SPEAKER_00]: If anybody else wanted to share anything, I know our next item is correspondence and announcements.

836
01:15:56,454 --> 01:16:02,157
[SPEAKER_00]: I have a couple of items, but before we move to that, I don't know if anybody else wanted to share something about Judy.

837
01:16:02,177 --> 01:16:05,718
[SPEAKER_00]: All right.

838
01:16:07,157 --> 01:16:08,078
[SPEAKER_02]: About Judy Heumann?

839
01:16:08,518 --> 01:16:09,259
[SPEAKER_00]: Yeah.

840
01:16:09,679 --> 01:16:11,720
[SPEAKER_00]: Go ahead, Melanie.

841
01:16:11,760 --> 01:16:18,805
[SPEAKER_00]: I sent out a video to the commission that, I can't remember his name, Dan Habib's son.

842
01:16:20,186 --> 01:16:20,626
[SPEAKER_09]: Samuel.

843
01:16:21,287 --> 01:16:24,029
[SPEAKER_00]: Yes, the interview that he did with Judy.

844
01:16:24,329 --> 01:16:24,669
[SPEAKER_00]: Judy, yeah.

845
01:16:25,610 --> 01:16:31,914
[SPEAKER_09]: Oh, I did an interview with Judy and I kept meaning to get it to her and I felt terribly that I never did get it to her.

846
01:16:31,934 --> 01:16:34,596
[SPEAKER_09]: I did an interview with Judy and my mentor, Tom Hare.

847
01:16:35,384 --> 01:16:37,466
[SPEAKER_09]: at Harvard who was an inclusion expert.

848
01:16:37,546 --> 01:16:38,647
[SPEAKER_09]: And they were old friends.

849
01:16:38,687 --> 01:16:47,833
[SPEAKER_09]: They used to work together at OSEP, you know, back in the day when they were both younger working to reauthorize IDEA.

850
01:16:48,854 --> 01:17:00,022
[SPEAKER_09]: So they tell all kinds of stories about that and just, you know, great friends and great woman and, you know, a lot of fun to be around and, you know, beautiful smile and you didn't want to be on her bad side because you would know.

851
01:17:02,084 --> 01:17:03,325
[SPEAKER_09]: And, you know, she was supposed to be

852
01:17:04,022 --> 01:17:09,085
[SPEAKER_09]: our keynote at the Federation for Children with Special Needs conference last week.

853
01:17:09,165 --> 01:17:14,528
[SPEAKER_09]: And we got a call, she was gonna be on on Friday as part of like a fireside chat kind of thing.

854
01:17:15,228 --> 01:17:21,532
[SPEAKER_09]: And we got a call on Thursday that she wasn't able to come and I think she died Friday morning.

855
01:17:21,672 --> 01:17:24,493
[SPEAKER_09]: So it was just devastating to so many.

856
01:17:24,653 --> 01:17:32,318
[SPEAKER_09]: And Judy helped so many people in the disability community, young people in particular, who just looked up to her so much as well.

857
01:17:33,507 --> 01:17:42,109
[SPEAKER_09]: When you see Crip Camp, if you haven't already seen it, you know, Judy is young and beautiful and a fighter and amazing in that film.

858
01:17:42,129 --> 01:17:53,311
[SPEAKER_09]: But, you know, even at, you know, 75 or whatever it was when she passed, she was as beautiful and vibrant and all of those things up until the day she left us.

859
01:17:53,351 --> 01:17:55,812
[SPEAKER_09]: So I hope people really enjoy her spirit.

860
01:17:55,832 --> 01:17:59,112
[SPEAKER_02]: Thank you.

861
01:18:03,416 --> 01:18:06,477
[SPEAKER_00]: Anybody have any correspondence or announcements that they want to share?

862
01:18:09,698 --> 01:18:11,199
[SPEAKER_07]: So I don't have anything.

863
01:18:11,379 --> 01:18:12,439
[SPEAKER_00]: Oh, go ahead, Gabby.

864
01:18:12,719 --> 01:18:12,999
[SPEAKER_07]: Sorry.

865
01:18:13,620 --> 01:18:22,923
[SPEAKER_08]: No, I was just going to say, I don't know, would this be an OK time to perhaps lay on the table my earlier motion with that?

866
01:18:23,523 --> 01:18:23,783
[SPEAKER_00]: Yes.

867
01:18:24,243 --> 01:18:25,364
[SPEAKER_00]: Go for it.

868
01:18:25,844 --> 01:18:28,965
[SPEAKER_09]: You want to make a motion to pick up from the table, Gabby?

869
01:18:29,752 --> 01:18:32,032
[SPEAKER_09]: pick up from the table, okay.

870
01:18:32,333 --> 01:18:34,573
[SPEAKER_07]: Still learning the terminology, but okay.

871
01:18:35,353 --> 01:18:39,074
[SPEAKER_07]: So is it a motion to, do you make a motion for that or do I just?

872
01:18:39,354 --> 01:18:43,995
[SPEAKER_09]: Yeah, you have to make a motion and then you have a second if they approve, and then you have a vote.

873
01:18:44,755 --> 01:18:54,597
[SPEAKER_09]: So make a motion to, you know, take that off the table, take from the table the motion that you had, and then you wanna state what the motion was and then if somebody seconds it.

874
01:18:55,597 --> 01:18:57,718
[SPEAKER_07]: Okay, I would like to,

875
01:18:59,722 --> 01:19:03,524
[SPEAKER_07]: Sorry, I have to move my car.

876
01:19:03,884 --> 01:19:08,706
[SPEAKER_07]: Sorry, I would like to, what was the word you used?

877
01:19:08,766 --> 01:19:12,667
[SPEAKER_08]: Sorry, not lay, put place on the table.

878
01:19:12,747 --> 01:19:14,028
[SPEAKER_08]: Like you're picking it up from the table.

879
01:19:14,528 --> 01:19:23,592
[SPEAKER_08]: Take from the table, my earlier motion to invite the ADA committee to our next meeting to facilitate more community planning.

880
01:19:25,492 --> 01:19:27,893
[SPEAKER_09]: So first you have to make the motion to take it from the table.

881
01:19:27,953 --> 01:19:29,174
[SPEAKER_09]: So you want to split the motion, sorry.

882
01:19:29,695 --> 01:19:33,638
[SPEAKER_09]: So Gabby, are you making a motion to take your initial motion from the table?

883
01:19:34,578 --> 01:19:37,781
[SPEAKER_07]: Yes, I am making a motion to take it from the table.

884
01:19:38,281 --> 01:19:39,602
[SPEAKER_01]: I second your motion, Gabby.

885
01:19:41,243 --> 01:19:41,623
[SPEAKER_00]: All in favor?

886
01:19:41,663 --> 01:19:42,364
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you, Linda.

887
01:19:45,506 --> 01:19:46,366
[SPEAKER_00]: Anyone opposed?

888
01:19:49,649 --> 01:19:50,489
[SPEAKER_00]: Anyone abstaining?

889
01:19:50,509 --> 01:19:52,611
[SPEAKER_00]: All right, motion carries.

890
01:19:53,271 --> 01:19:54,432
[SPEAKER_00]: Now your next motion, Gabby.

891
01:19:56,865 --> 01:20:01,929
[SPEAKER_08]: I would like to make a motion to invite the ADA committee to our next meeting.

892
01:20:05,291 --> 01:20:07,193
[SPEAKER_09]: The Medford Public Schools ADA committee?

893
01:20:08,173 --> 01:20:08,434
[SPEAKER_09]: Yes.

894
01:20:09,554 --> 01:20:13,077
[SPEAKER_00]: Anyone want to second that?

895
01:20:14,778 --> 01:20:15,699
[SPEAKER_01]: Yes, I will second.

896
01:20:18,020 --> 01:20:18,621
[SPEAKER_02]: All in favor?

897
01:20:21,883 --> 01:20:22,804
[SPEAKER_02]: Anyone opposed?

898
01:20:24,345 --> 01:20:25,346
[SPEAKER_02]: Great, motion carries.

899
01:20:28,630 --> 01:20:29,371
[SPEAKER_00]: Thank you, Gabby.

900
01:20:30,531 --> 01:20:31,012
[SPEAKER_00]: That's great.

901
01:20:31,032 --> 01:20:37,056
[SPEAKER_09]: So now will someone from one of the commissioners send an email or maybe, you know, Francis certainly knows the committee, she's on it.

902
01:20:37,556 --> 01:20:41,719
[SPEAKER_09]: So maybe through work with Francis to send an email invitation to the committee.

903
01:20:41,739 --> 01:20:45,342
[SPEAKER_00]: Yes, I can do that.

904
01:20:48,764 --> 01:20:49,245
[SPEAKER_02]: Thank you.

